00:48.882 --> 00:53.621
Southern Italy,
the heel of the boot.

00:55.556 --> 00:59.427
Remote, vast open spaces.

00:59.460 --> 01:04.132
The red earth here
has a magnetic pull.

01:04.165 --> 01:04.665
♪

01:08.302 --> 01:13.241
Raw, alternately charming
and savage.

01:13.274 --> 01:13.774
♪

01:21.449 --> 01:21.949
♪

01:39.267 --> 01:39.767
♪

01:47.708 --> 01:48.208
♪

02:03.624 --> 02:05.359
Grazie.

02:05.393 --> 02:07.995
Now, in the annals of food,

02:08.027 --> 02:10.298
this is like a divisive dish.

02:10.330 --> 02:13.601
Basically anything with ricci,
also known as uni.

02:13.634 --> 02:15.936
We call it sea urchin roe.

02:15.969 --> 02:19.106
This is truly one of
the greatest things on Earth.

02:19.139 --> 02:19.639
♪

02:24.212 --> 02:26.247
God damn.

02:32.853 --> 02:34.855
Despite its uncanny beauty,

02:34.888 --> 02:37.958
southern Italy's Puglia
and Basilicata regions

02:37.991 --> 02:40.194
are some of the least populated,

02:40.228 --> 02:41.729
least visited,

02:41.762 --> 02:44.898
least known parts
of the country...

02:58.111 --> 03:02.816
A mix of sea, hills, valleys,
and rich earth.

03:02.850 --> 03:07.120
The food here is Italian
but completely its own.

03:10.391 --> 03:14.862
A little garlic, pepperoncino,
parsley.

03:16.430 --> 03:20.634
Sea urchin, some kind of fish,
Fumane.

03:24.104 --> 03:27.275
Pasta.
That's it.

03:27.308 --> 03:29.710
Oh, incredible.

03:35.749 --> 03:39.420
Never been to this part
of Italy before.

03:39.453 --> 03:41.722
A lot of blue here.

03:41.755 --> 03:46.226
Light browns and ochres
and white.

03:46.260 --> 03:47.821
I don't know; you just look
at this place.

03:47.828 --> 03:51.131
It demands a big space.

03:51.164 --> 03:53.100
As I walk around,
I'm always humming

03:53.133 --> 03:56.470
these Ennio Morricone scores:

03:56.504 --> 04:00.808
"For a Few Dollars More,"
"Once Upon a Time in the West."

04:00.841 --> 04:01.341
♪

04:12.453 --> 04:15.022
Oh, this is so good.

04:19.026 --> 04:20.894
Makes you want
to start smoking again.

04:20.928 --> 04:23.096
Oh, grazie.

04:30.771 --> 04:33.173
Oh, God, that's good.

04:35.543 --> 04:38.446
Jesus.

04:38.479 --> 04:38.979
♪

04:52.726 --> 04:56.096
Feudal, ungovernable,
it was believed once

04:56.129 --> 04:58.532
that civilization
and Christianity

04:58.566 --> 05:01.034
would never reach this far south

05:01.068 --> 05:03.704
into the hill of Italy's boot.

05:06.740 --> 05:07.240
♪

05:11.912 --> 05:14.848
A lawless land
filled with folklore

05:14.882 --> 05:18.218
and tales of spirits
and possession,

05:18.251 --> 05:22.823
a blood soup
of Christianity and Paganism.

05:41.274 --> 05:44.244
I had an extremely handsome
brother,

05:44.277 --> 05:46.580
and I was a little...
I was like an elf,

05:46.614 --> 05:49.082
so I kind of didn't get
the attention from the mother

05:49.116 --> 05:50.918
that my brother did.

05:50.951 --> 05:54.822
I had very big lips as a child,
and she always used to say

05:54.855 --> 05:56.924
that I should have
plastic surgery.

05:56.957 --> 05:58.692
But when you see my daughter,
Sofia,

05:58.726 --> 06:00.093
she's got my lips.

06:00.127 --> 06:02.896
- Yeah.
- But they look good on her.

06:02.930 --> 06:06.500
Up in the mountains, you find
tiny medieval-era villages

06:06.534 --> 06:09.870
like Bernalda, seat of
the paternal family roots

06:09.903 --> 06:12.773
of this man,
Francis Ford Coppola...

06:12.806 --> 06:13.774
Welcome.
Benvenuto.

06:13.807 --> 06:15.443
Thank you.

06:15.476 --> 06:18.912
One of the greatest filmmakers
of all time.

06:18.946 --> 06:21.281
You have deep roots here.

06:21.314 --> 06:25.419
My grandfather always told
us stories of Bernalda,

06:25.453 --> 06:26.787
Bernalda Bella.

06:26.820 --> 06:28.789
And oddly enough,
he never had gone back

06:28.822 --> 06:32.292
once he left
as an American immigrant.

06:32.325 --> 06:34.862
But it became mythical to me.

06:34.895 --> 06:39.132
The story is that the family
originally came from Lecce,

06:39.166 --> 06:41.134
and someone got
the sister pregnant,

06:41.168 --> 06:42.870
and they killed her.

06:42.903 --> 06:45.072
And then they became briganti,

06:45.105 --> 06:47.307
so they were one step
ahead of the law.

06:47.340 --> 06:51.078
And then they settled down
and became laborers

06:51.111 --> 06:52.913
in the olive fields.

06:52.946 --> 06:56.750
And that's really the origins
of the Coppola family.

06:56.784 --> 07:00.588
Because the south was
so oppressed by the north,

07:00.621 --> 07:02.490
it stayed the same.

07:02.523 --> 07:05.793
They haven't had 1,000 years
of cheap, "gyp the tourist."

07:05.826 --> 07:07.521
And you come, and you can walk
out in the street,

07:07.528 --> 07:09.329
and you're in
a real Italian town

07:09.362 --> 07:11.298
where the people don't know
anything about...

07:11.331 --> 07:12.859
They'll invite you
to the house for dinner here

07:12.866 --> 07:14.434
quite innocently.

07:14.468 --> 07:16.937
How long that will last,
I don't know.

07:16.970 --> 07:18.572
♪

07:18.606 --> 07:19.973
What we're looking at here

07:20.007 --> 07:22.009
is food I thought
you'd get a kick out of,

07:22.042 --> 07:23.911
lampascioni,

07:23.944 --> 07:25.779
or what my family call...

07:25.813 --> 07:27.648
It's the bulb of a flower,
the hyacinth.

07:27.681 --> 07:29.483
Wow.

07:29.517 --> 07:31.619
You score it, and then
you put it in a deep fryer,

07:31.652 --> 07:32.953
and that turns it into a flower.

07:32.986 --> 07:35.523
Beautiful.

07:35.556 --> 07:37.525
Oh, wow.

07:37.558 --> 07:38.992
This is incredible.

07:39.026 --> 07:41.495
So you may have some history
with this house.

07:41.529 --> 07:42.963
I mean, it was...

07:42.996 --> 07:44.224
Your grandfather
was boning the help here?

07:44.231 --> 07:45.165
It was...

07:45.198 --> 07:46.767
You know... heard that story.

07:46.800 --> 07:49.670
My grandfather was...
They called him zumpa balcone.

07:49.703 --> 07:50.871
He was girl crazy.

07:50.904 --> 07:54.675
And he would go up on the roof

07:54.708 --> 07:59.112
and go down to where
the maid was, Palmetta,

07:59.146 --> 08:02.349
and conduct this affair.

08:02.382 --> 08:04.552
And so when I found this place
years later,

08:04.585 --> 08:08.021
there was, in fact, a roof
leading to a housemaid's.

08:08.055 --> 08:12.660
And I fantasize that perhaps
that was where it happened.

08:12.693 --> 08:17.565
Dove... where's...
We have to have more food.

08:17.598 --> 08:20.200
Bring the secondo.

08:20.233 --> 08:23.571
This is a dish we called
the coldane.

08:23.604 --> 08:24.672
How do you call it?

08:24.705 --> 08:26.006
Cotenna.

08:26.039 --> 08:27.541
This is basically...
My father said...

08:27.575 --> 08:28.769
- Pigskin.
- This is the football.

08:28.776 --> 08:29.977
Wait a minute.

08:30.010 --> 08:31.344
You had this
at your dinner table

08:31.378 --> 08:32.880
as, like, a young man, as a kid?

08:32.913 --> 08:34.347
- Yeah, a little kid.
- Wow.

08:34.381 --> 08:36.750
- I hated it.
- Of course.

08:36.784 --> 08:38.385
But now I don't.

08:42.590 --> 08:44.256
Oh, so good.

08:44.291 --> 08:45.593
Mmm.

08:45.626 --> 08:47.761
We're dining
at Palazzo Margherita,

08:47.795 --> 08:51.699
not the ancestral home
of generations of Coppolas

08:51.732 --> 08:54.401
but might well have been
the one-time manor house

08:54.434 --> 08:56.103
of those who lorded over them

08:56.136 --> 08:57.905
while they worked in the fields.

08:57.938 --> 09:01.541
During Mussolini time,
every town had a podestà,

09:01.575 --> 09:03.443
the official
of the fascist party.

09:03.476 --> 09:04.612
Right.

09:04.645 --> 09:06.279
And this family was the podestà.

09:06.313 --> 09:11.118
The ladies here were
so, you know, snobby.

09:11.151 --> 09:12.419
We are low-class Italians.

09:12.452 --> 09:15.388
They were
more high-class Italians.

09:15.422 --> 09:17.758
It took years and a lot of money

09:17.791 --> 09:21.294
converting the once-grand
but decaying mansion

09:21.328 --> 09:23.396
into a boutique hotel.

09:23.430 --> 09:25.132
You know, when you bought
this place,

09:25.165 --> 09:27.635
is there a sense of vengeance?

09:27.668 --> 09:29.737
I... you know, by then,

09:29.770 --> 09:32.640
"The Godfather" had come out
40 years ago.

09:32.673 --> 09:34.642
No, no, I mean, look.
It's not about the film.

09:34.675 --> 09:38.912
It's about...
a historical correction.

09:38.946 --> 09:40.247
There's a saying.

09:40.280 --> 09:42.650
You know what
Italian Alzheimer's is?

09:42.683 --> 09:43.984
Do you know what it is?

09:44.017 --> 09:46.153
You forget everything
but the grudge.

09:47.688 --> 09:50.323
This is the only
internal garden in Basilicata.

09:50.357 --> 09:52.325
I don't think
any of the normal people

09:52.359 --> 09:53.927
had ever been permitted
to visit it.

09:53.961 --> 09:55.462
Right.

09:55.495 --> 09:57.230
So I was happy
that normal people

09:57.264 --> 10:00.233
were gonna be here.

10:00.267 --> 10:02.269
"The Godfather" was a weird
experience in my life,

10:02.302 --> 10:04.905
because it was so much
more successful

10:04.938 --> 10:07.641
than I could have ever
anticipated

10:07.675 --> 10:10.510
so that I became well-known
around the world

10:10.543 --> 10:13.180
in ways that was
almost embarrassing.

10:13.213 --> 10:14.447
And so when I came here,

10:14.481 --> 10:16.316
they made me
an honorary citizen,

10:16.349 --> 10:19.519
and they had the little
schoolchildren out in a parade.

10:19.552 --> 10:21.955
And if I think about it,
as a new kid in a school,

10:21.989 --> 10:24.758
my greatest fear
was embarrassment.

10:24.792 --> 10:27.427
"Oh, here's Francis.
He's a new student."

10:27.460 --> 10:29.329
"Oh, Francis is a girl's name."

10:29.362 --> 10:31.932
I was embarrassed
in front of everyone,

10:31.965 --> 10:33.433
and I was a total outsider.

10:33.466 --> 10:34.968
And then when I became...

10:35.002 --> 10:36.536
On the other side
of "The Godfather,"

10:36.569 --> 10:39.439
when I became so well-known,
I was also an outsider.

10:39.472 --> 10:41.208
So I've always been an outsider.

10:41.241 --> 10:42.876
What's in there?

10:42.910 --> 10:45.645
- Some lamb chops and...
- Oh, lamb chops, okay.

10:45.679 --> 10:47.114
Some lamb head.

10:47.147 --> 10:48.716
Oh, the capuzzelle is in there?

10:48.749 --> 10:50.350
It's all there.

10:50.383 --> 10:51.745
So you're getting
a whole lamb's head?

10:51.752 --> 10:54.054
Oh, look at this.
Here we go.

10:54.087 --> 10:55.315
Come on out.
Oh, that's very good.

10:55.322 --> 10:56.690
Is this for me?

10:56.724 --> 10:59.793
- Give me your plate.
- Oh, yeah. Mmm.

10:59.827 --> 11:02.195
Oh, this is fantastic.

11:02.229 --> 11:03.396
Come here, little one.

11:03.430 --> 11:05.065
Hello, sweetie pie.
Hello.

11:05.098 --> 11:06.566
This is my friend.

11:06.599 --> 11:09.837
No, we went out last night,
and it was so great.

11:09.870 --> 11:12.339
We went to the local circus.

11:12.372 --> 11:15.909
The tigers and giraffe
and water oxen.

11:15.943 --> 11:17.210
Did you go to the circus?

11:17.244 --> 11:18.545
Was it good?

11:18.578 --> 11:20.380
Cool.
What was your favorite part?

11:20.413 --> 11:25.385
Um, when the giant
fake gorilla came.

11:50.944 --> 11:51.444
♪

12:04.825 --> 12:05.325
♪

12:21.341 --> 12:23.376
The smell, the...

12:23.410 --> 12:26.146
The smell of the port,
some dead fish.

12:26.179 --> 12:27.714
It's not fresh fish.
It's dead fish.

12:27.747 --> 12:29.082
I don't hate that smell either.

12:29.116 --> 12:31.418
No, no.

12:31.451 --> 12:33.453
Today, we fish.

12:47.434 --> 12:50.270
For once, I'm confident
of success

12:50.303 --> 12:53.673
with Dino and Franco and their
trusty wooden gozzo,

12:53.706 --> 12:55.542
as they call these boats.

12:57.044 --> 12:59.612
And for good luck,
I have Asia Argento along,

12:59.646 --> 13:01.815
who, in addition to directing
and acting in films

13:01.849 --> 13:03.984
for, like, the last 30 years,

13:04.017 --> 13:07.320
has spent a hell of a lot
of time doing this.

13:30.243 --> 13:32.545
You have never done this?
I've done this.

13:32.579 --> 13:34.514
I've stood there and watched
somebody else do it.

13:37.217 --> 13:39.019
Scorpionfish.
Oh, nice.

13:39.052 --> 13:40.153
A little one.

13:40.187 --> 13:41.588
Okay, Anthony, take over.

13:48.761 --> 13:51.564
It's... yeah, your forearms.

13:51.598 --> 13:54.234
It's good for the hangover.
No, forearm.

13:54.267 --> 13:56.036
It's very good for the hangover.

13:59.272 --> 14:01.008
Oh!

14:02.542 --> 14:04.211
Beautiful.

14:04.244 --> 14:07.480
You're making her talk
like a little hand puppet too.

14:07.514 --> 14:12.219
Yeah, "Hey, you had
too much to drink last night."

14:20.360 --> 14:22.629
Don't.

14:32.973 --> 14:34.741
There's no word for "hangover"?

14:34.774 --> 14:36.302
We have to invent a word
for "hangover."

14:36.309 --> 14:37.848
It's incredibly optimistic
and unusual.

14:37.877 --> 14:41.048
I know. There's none,
because it's shameful.

14:41.081 --> 14:44.317
- Oh.
- Ohhhhh!

14:56.829 --> 14:58.331
Hey!

15:46.846 --> 15:48.848
I want to see
what's inside his guts.

15:48.881 --> 15:51.484
Maybe a half-digested Speedo.

15:53.453 --> 15:56.089
Ah, look at all this goodness.

15:56.123 --> 15:58.258
You know, you're enjoying
that a little too much.

16:00.527 --> 16:02.195
Any notions I had

16:02.229 --> 16:04.497
of spending an idyllic
afternoon by the shore

16:04.531 --> 16:06.533
are quickly dashed
when I discover

16:06.566 --> 16:09.169
it's a religious holiday,

16:09.202 --> 16:11.871
which apparently means
Italians grease up,

16:11.904 --> 16:14.207
strap on
their tiniest bathing suits,

16:14.241 --> 16:16.576
and hit the beach en masse.

16:24.684 --> 16:25.184
♪

16:34.194 --> 16:36.463
Our intrepid fisher folk
and some friends collaborate

16:36.496 --> 16:41.901
with Asia and me on a
picnic/barbecue/beach party.

16:41.934 --> 16:44.337
Okay, and the two lobsters?

16:44.371 --> 16:47.006
Ha, look at all that roe.

16:47.040 --> 16:50.577
Look at that.

17:01.588 --> 17:02.088
♪

17:06.093 --> 17:07.527
And the sauce...

17:07.560 --> 17:09.596
See, all those little fish
paid off.

17:09.628 --> 17:10.128
♪

17:20.140 --> 17:22.842
Pop it in already.
My God.

17:22.875 --> 17:26.279
No waiting.
Good, I'm in. I'm in.

17:27.646 --> 17:30.083
They're hungry.
They're starving.

17:31.651 --> 17:33.453
Mmm, superb.

17:33.486 --> 17:34.787
It's good.

17:34.821 --> 17:37.090
"Joe."

17:40.160 --> 17:43.563
The lobster looks great.
Mama mia.

18:04.016 --> 18:06.786
- This is incredible.
- These are incredible.

18:06.819 --> 18:09.422
- They're so sweet and...
- Yeah.

18:09.456 --> 18:09.956
♪

18:30.943 --> 18:34.814
Oh, look at this.

18:40.119 --> 18:41.087
♪

18:44.891 --> 18:46.526
This is
a uniquely Italian thing.

18:46.559 --> 18:48.761
- With the Speedos.
- The banana hammock.

18:48.795 --> 18:51.097
- The what?
- Banana hammock.

18:52.732 --> 18:55.502
In America, people don't want
to get a tan like this.

18:55.535 --> 18:57.563
They don't want to reveal
that much about themselves.

18:57.570 --> 18:58.971
It takes the mystery out of...

18:59.005 --> 19:00.707
- So they wear the...
- Big boxers.

19:00.740 --> 19:02.442
Keep them guessing
until it's too late.

19:15.922 --> 19:17.557
He say it's like
an elephant trunk.

19:17.590 --> 19:18.991
It can grow incredibly.

19:19.025 --> 19:21.394
Oh, he's a grower, not a shower.

19:31.671 --> 19:32.171
♪

19:56.863 --> 19:57.363
♪

20:07.474 --> 20:07.974
♪

20:23.490 --> 20:25.525
The heel of Italy's boot
has been referred to

20:25.558 --> 20:27.760
as "the land of remorse,"

20:27.794 --> 20:30.297
la terra del rimorso,

20:30.330 --> 20:35.768
which also translates
to "land of the rebitten."

20:57.690 --> 21:01.494
Here, in this harsh landscape,
lives the tarantula

21:01.528 --> 21:06.666
and echoes of some deep, dark
pre-Christian paganship,

21:06.699 --> 21:08.601
like tarantism.

21:12.839 --> 21:16.175
A dance, a ritual, an exorcism,

21:16.208 --> 21:20.279
an expression
of unspeakable desires.

21:20.313 --> 21:20.813
♪

21:29.322 --> 21:31.257
What is this?

21:31.290 --> 21:32.359
Humble local wine.

21:32.392 --> 21:33.660
It's rustica.

21:33.693 --> 21:35.928
- Rustico.
- Rustico.

21:38.965 --> 21:39.465
♪

21:49.909 --> 21:51.611
We are at the humble masseria.

21:51.644 --> 21:53.613
Now, what is a masseria?

21:53.646 --> 21:56.816
A masseria is a place
that was the bigger house

21:56.849 --> 21:58.351
where the family would stay

21:58.385 --> 22:01.354
and then the farmers,
the animals.

22:01.388 --> 22:03.890
- It's a plantation.
- It's a plantation.

22:03.923 --> 22:05.324
And this would be the big house.

22:10.997 --> 22:11.497
♪

22:19.939 --> 22:23.976
It's like at your place
in America, Hookers.

22:24.010 --> 22:25.878
No, it's Hooters.

22:25.912 --> 22:27.847
- Hooters.
- Hooters.

22:27.880 --> 22:30.249
Local Apulian superstition
has it,

22:30.282 --> 22:32.218
if a tarantula bit someone,

22:32.251 --> 22:34.353
most often a woman
while she worked the fields,

22:34.387 --> 22:36.556
it could lead to some
pretty direct and disturbing

22:36.589 --> 22:40.493
demonstrations
of carnality and desire,

22:40.527 --> 22:44.263
the victim tortured by
something supernatural, toxic,

22:44.296 --> 22:46.332
for which
there was only one cure.

22:46.365 --> 22:49.736
La tarantella is a kind
of music that was played

22:49.769 --> 22:52.872
for those women
who are possessed,

22:52.905 --> 22:54.941
bit by the tarantula.

22:54.974 --> 22:58.445
All of a sudden,
a woman will be on the floor,

22:58.478 --> 22:59.779
speaking in tongues and...

22:59.812 --> 23:02.449
Oh, the family
doesn't know what to do.

23:02.482 --> 23:03.783
There was only one remedy:

23:03.816 --> 23:05.618
calling the musicians in.

23:05.652 --> 23:11.190
They will have this kind of
ecstatic and orgasmic moment

23:11.223 --> 23:13.092
where they were released

23:13.125 --> 23:17.697
from this ultimately sexual
possession.

23:17.730 --> 23:18.230
♪

23:26.338 --> 23:29.208
Over the generations,
the Catholic Church absorbed

23:29.241 --> 23:31.644
ancient pagan traditions
like tarantism.

23:31.678 --> 23:33.980
And the ritualistic, frenzied
music and dance

23:34.013 --> 23:35.982
associated with it

23:36.015 --> 23:37.484
evolved into what we know today

23:37.517 --> 23:39.919
as pizzica and tarantella.

23:39.952 --> 23:41.353
♪

24:34.707 --> 24:35.207
♪

24:57.029 --> 24:58.665
While elsewhere in Europe,

24:58.698 --> 25:01.367
belief in afflictions
like tarantism died off,

25:01.400 --> 25:05.071
down here, old-school rituals
are still practiced.

